  <Notes>
    <Note Caller="1" LanguageCode="en" LastEdited="" LastEditedBy="">
      <References>
        <Reference>01201002400044</Reference>
      </References>
      <Content>Most commentators have argued that the verb should be read as a piel instead of a niphal</Content>
    </Note>
    <Note Caller="2" LanguageCode="en" LastEdited="" LastEditedBy="">
      <References>
        <Reference>01903301700022</Reference>
      </References>
      <Content>Although the passive of σῴζω in the LXX implies the reading of
a niph (יִמָּלֵט) cf. Tg) rather than the piel, the verb may not require revocalisation. There may be an implied indefinite object, and the Peshitta does include an object in its translation (see piel Versions, Peshitta).</Content>
    </Note>
    <Note Caller="3" LanguageCode="en" LastEdited="" LastEditedBy="">
      <References>
        <Reference>03000201500024</Reference>
      </References>
      <Content>The passive of διασῴζω in the LXX implies the reading of the
niphal (יִמָּלֵט) cf. Vg, Tg, Pesh), but this may be a characteristic alteration by the Versions to assist the sense. The piel, if retained, would have to be interpreted as intransitive, or to share the same object נפשׁו with the verb in the next line.</Content>
    </Note>
  </Notes>
  <ContributorNote>(b) Gloss: 6. Exegesis, A.1, p. 3. </ContributorNote>
